text:
we walk around dumping poison from our own infections upon others, rather than taking the time to tend to our own wounds.
~
we hurt and we pour that hurt into the hearts & souls of our brothers and sisters. we pass it along. here; take it, we say. now you know what it feels like to have a broken heart, a broken family, shattered hopes and dreams. now you feel the hurt i have carried my entire life. i didn‚Äôt ask for it, and neither did you, but now it‚Äôs yours.
~
your suffering is welcomed by the wounds of those around you. it makes the suffering feel less alone, if you wallow in the depths of hell with them.
~
our loved ones often carry the weight of the world on their shoulders that their family passed onto them, and it is passed to you to bare.
~
you take it. bullets in the heart. daggers in the flesh. a beating to your soul.
~
it‚Äôs heavy, carrying the trauma, the venom that was spread down ancestral lines.
~
but now you are faced with a very powerful choice, one that can set all who have come before you free. you have a choice, the moment the blades enter your flesh, and carve into your wounding, old and new.
~
you can take that blade and slice it into another, spreading the infection and pain. you can take those bullets, and lodge them into those around you. you can keep passing the pain back and forth, pulling you and another party deeper and deeper into pain and suffering.
~
or, you can pull those blades out, and bury them in the earth. you can pull them out, one by one, feeling all of the pain in the depths of your being as you do so. you can tend to each wound with compassion, gently pouring it‚Äôs healing salve into them.
~
you can thank the one who dumped their pain into you, for creating something so beautiful in your soul, a true gift to this planet.
~
when we are hurt, we are presented an opportunity. we can build up our protective shields to help us dodge the bullets, sending them ricocheting back into the one who shot them, or we can let them sink into our heart, allowing us to feel again, even if it stings in the moment. we can let that pain awaken a level of compassion that would otherwise remain dormant. we can choose to keep our walls ‚ù§Ô∏ècont‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
have you ever felt so lost? like never before. lost in your own thoughts which actually gives you the most beautiful time with your ownself sometimes, but the reality check kills you. similarly sometimes your own thoughts are the worst dagger to kill your own self. you all wanna escape out from this. many of you had harder times in your life and maybe you all still are facing which is the only thing we can do. eeh we can't control feelings for sure but we can try to find a happy side inside us. of course if there's a negative dump face is there so there must be pretty good happier place too where you can escape and rest your nerves. to be lost is totally okay, the conclusion i'll qoute lines of the late beautiful lady who said "time doesn't remain same, either bad or good" so this is where we are. live life to the fullest we all know we deserve happiness but let time to manage things. 
stay blessed guys 
signing off (ts)
.

text:
many young girls seem to be under the impression that sex was never meant to be pleasurable for them, that it is something you do to please your future partner. wrong.

sex being solely a thing to pleasure a man is a sexist notion that is still kind of held up by society. we still tell our girls that they probably won't enjoy sex, they won't orgasm, that they shouldn't expect anything. we tell them men get all the pleasure and that's the way it is. it's disgusting. you find your way, what works for you, what makes you feel good. don't settle for shitty sex just because society has said you aren't meant to enjoy it.

same goes for boys/men. stop telling them they are supposed love sex. stop telling them that they cannot reject sex or shame them for not wanting sex. go at your own pace and don't let anybody belittle nor mock you for not wanting sex. your consent is just as important.

text:
i started getting hooked on watching tik tok videos, because most of the ones i saw would make me smile because they were funny, and laughter is great medicine, however something i have seen more and lately right across social media, was an alarming number of young girls crying out for help, holding so much pain inside, sharing that on social media only to be bullied, judged, and even one i saw was told to go kill herself. and people sit back and wonder how can new zealand have the highest rates of teen suicide . this is exactly why. i wrote this poem today, purely from observations. ‚ù§Ô∏èüß°üíõüíöüíôüíúüåàü¶Ñüßò‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüíäüí™üìùüëßüó£Ô∏è i see all these young girls living on social media,
being called out, bullied and judged for the world they live in.
the names they are called, the gossip that is spread,
building up, when there are only so many tears they can shed. 
trapped in these deep and dark places where they feel so alone,
abandoned in this maze of emotions they can't escape from.
but if you look past the front they portray to the camera,
you can see the hurt and pain swallowing them up amongst the drama.
some are more obvious when crying out for help,
others suffer silently hiding behind their masks of doubt.
they get told to suck it up and stop being so dramatic,
then eventually the pain they carry becomes automatic.
hashtag it will be ok, hashtag you are not alone,
this means absolutely nothing when they post "it's over" one last time from their phone. 
#choosinghappiness #soberlife #asdmamma #makingpositivechanges #mindbodysoulspirit #iamfullycommited #metoo #thisisme #healingispower #iamnotalone #igotthis #iamworthit #iamawarrior #iamasurvivor #shininglightintothedarkness #bethelight #beingpresent #breakingfree #onedayatatime #deppression #anxiety #ptsd #bethechangeyouwanttoseeintheworld

text: feeling inspired to launch a new coaching workshop and program based on the requests, conversations and client questions i receive on the regular. i‚Äôm honored to create a safe container to explore difficult and exciting parts of ourselves and our culture, such that we can all benefit from the profound shift in which we find ourselvesüí• sex! always exciting and particularly fraught these days. wanna talk about #metoo? or how sexy consent is? or the difference between sex and intimacy, and why it matters? ü§©üò≥drugs/medicine! how do you shift consciousness? curious about the movement to legalize psychedelics? wanna talk about the latest understandings of addiction? üåãüíÄdeath: that which we fear and do not confront tends to run our lives until faced. we experience multiple deaths throughout our lives and rebirths, as well. how do you handle the little deaths along your road? at the end, death is the only door out and along the way, the frame which enlivens every breath we take. what‚Äôs your relationship to your own end? üëª- let‚Äôs come together in a non-judge mental circle to explore the human experience through the lens of sex, drugs/medicine and our inevitable ending of this material experience in death. ‚ú® hosting online and in person, sliding scale, with individual coaching options, too. üòç who‚Äôs interested? comment or dm me - i‚Äôll be polling early birds to fine tune our explorations üíï#sexdrugsanddeath #sexdrugs #coaching #shadowcoaching #conversationsthatmatter #sex #drugs #death #talkaboutit

text:
when skydance media chief executive #davidellison announced this year that he was¬†hiring #johnlasseter to head skydance animation, many in and outside the company were¬†shocked and deeply unhappy. only months earlier, lasseter had ended his relationship with pixar ‚Äî where he had worked since the early ‚Äô80s ‚Äî and parent company disney after multiple allegations of inappropriate behavior and the creation of a frat house-like work environment. lasseter had admitted to inappropriate hugging and ‚Äúother missteps.‚Äù after announcing the hire, ellison sent a long email to staff, noting that lasseter was contractually obligated to behave professionally, and convened a series of town halls in which lasseter¬†apologized for past behavior¬†and asked to be given the chance to prove himself to his new staff. meanwhile, mireille soria, president of paramount pictures animation, with which skydance has a distribution deal, took the highly unusual step of meeting with female employees to tell them that they could decline to work with lasseter.

john lasseter‚Äôs return proves that hollywood still does not understand the damage he did

but it was #emmathompson, the politically outspoken¬†newly anointed dame commander of the british empirewho made the first real definitive statement on lasseter, and one of the most significant decisions in¬†post-#metoo hollywood.

in mid-february, it was reported that the two-time oscar winner¬†had pulled out of skydance‚Äôs highly touted animation feature ‚Äúluck,‚Äù¬†citing her concerns about lasseter‚Äôs hiring. according to her representatives, from the moment the hire was announced, thompson began conversations about extricating herself from the project; she officially withdrew jan. 20.

in a letter she sent to #skydance management three days later, she acknowledged the complications caused by a star withdrawing from a project, including the effect her decision would have on the director, the rest of the cast and the crew. but in the end, she wrote, the questions raised by the lasseter hire made it impossible for her to remain in the film.

thompson declined to comment on her decision, but she made the letter available to @latimes

text:
brands that completely suck are the ones that lack clarity on who they are. because of this, they steal from those who do!
.
here in trinidad and tobago, especially amongst the small business community, you'll find so called brands, public figures and coaches who prey on the ignorance of others constantly. another downfall to it is friends of these said people who instead of calling them out on this shit, praise them for their ¬†heist.
.
setting yourself up to look like something you're not! this is what it looks like when you have no focus in your business. a side effect of a generic, undifferentiated "brand". you begin to play games with unsuspecting clients. so it becomes less and less about the clients needs and if you can *actually* meet them and more about *money*
.
this is not what is mean't by "follow what he is doing". what you want to do, is focus all your energy inward, think about what you are most passionate about and give your point of view concerning it a platform to be heard by staying true to what ever that voice sounds like.
.
outside of that, you're just another copy cat to ignore and loath...possibly even prosecute.
.

text:
the strippers in los angeles are hot under the collar about new state laws that changed the nature of their business relationship with club owners. what was billed as a way to ensure fair pay for the dancers has wound up costing them money and done nothing to alleviate other complaints about issues they run into while working. now they‚Äôre going on strike because they want to see some improvements and they‚Äôre getting some support from representatives of the #metoo movement. (cbs los angeles)

a group of adult dancers says they aren‚Äôt getting a fair shake at los angeles strip clubs, and it‚Äôs in part because of a california court ruling.

the group calls themselves ‚Äúsoldiers of pole‚Äù and they‚Äôre picketing outside the crazy girls club in hollywood where they‚Äôre demanding, among other things, fair wages. they say a state court ruling changed their status from independent contractors to actual employees.

the dancers say now that clubs have to pay the women an hourly wage, management has been keeping a much larger chunk of their tips. they also claim that some clubs have been stealing their wages and charging dancers new fees ever since the new ruling, and they want it to stop.

this seems like yet another classic example of how ‚Äúwell‚Äù the government can do when it decides to step in and regulate how businesses operate in the private sector. we‚Äôre not talking about workplace safety regulations here or even working conditions or hours. california ended the ability of clubs to hire dancers as independent contractors.

these ‚Äúsoldiers of the pole‚Äù have been talking to everyone from labor unions to the aclu, along with the folks from #metoo. under the old system, dancers might not even be paid any wages by the club. they would instead be given (or pay for) a slot in the lineup. but all the money they brought in from tips should have been going right in their pockets. (some clubs apparently had tip-sharing policies for the bar staff.) now that they are minimum wage employees of the club, they may qualify for certain benefits, but the management is scooping up most of their tips. the really popular dancers who did a couple of sets in an hour when the club was crowded could

text:
when the reality comes to plain sight.. yup i'm not moving much further it's up to my waste so shoveled as much as possible my face is burning and i'm in the mood for some beautiful freshly baked cannabis cookies to take some of the fire away

i'm still breathing laughing singing and occasionally blowing smoke out like pete the magic dragon

#crpsawareness i refuse to let u defeat me.. so i may have to double my.. actually triple my doses bc my neuro system loves the funky chicken dance.

oh yeah shaking my booty regardless of whether it knows it's going to or not.

ok peeps as u know by now... #comedyismyremedy #mindysfight is your fight 
hello #stemcells shove them rt into my #spinalcord if u want just find an everlasting flipping cure. i'm on fire and not like the beautiful #aliciakeys #thisgirlisonfire 
#researchers #medical and #biological studies alike.. i believe there is a cure, and i am on a mission to find it...or die working on the cure myself... i am writing on this platform to serve as 2 things. 1) journal to streamline where i have been with this specific disorder since 2014

i beat 3 comas multiple surgeries and half of my gut was pulled out in 3 separate very large surgeries... i will never forget where i came from nor do i need a reminder of where i am headed.

i need to remind myself to be kind, patient, loving, and nurturing individual i am to others, and start using it to believe the things the universe has set for my path to ride and those willing participants who want to come along feel free to enter in this wild journey we call life.
from the midst of chaos to inner stillness.
this is what i have finally come to find.
my voice, both thunderous and yes the whispers are loud 
my spirit is loud & i am very proud of who i have become today.
#mindysfight is your fight #metoo
#silentnomore i got my voice back and my trachea is starting to feel much better as i continue to do therapy for speech and cognition i have never been more humbled in all of my life.
i genuinely appreciate you all 
#minsicle 5ft under fresh powder and it will have to wait another day.
i am grateful for my legs and my arms along with my healing spine #nevergiveup

text:
this past weekend as part of our black history art celebration we featured the trailer screening of @quietandclearfilm and met one of the film's star characters @johniseeee ms. johnise "peezoo" bowie.  here is the trailer.  follow them to keep track of their progress in the film festival circuit.  #supportthearts ***message from the director***
in october 2017, the same month #metoo went viral, @andreverdunjones ¬†andre verdun jones ‚Äì co-founder of the black lgbtq publication the tenth magazine¬†and executive producer of award winning short film mr. okra ‚Äì invited me to his hometown of franklin, louisiana after seeing my experimental short film dixieland (filmed in new orleans). jones encouraged me to expand on its themes in a short film. 
upon arriving in franklin, intersectional feminism was quickly becoming a talking point online and i was curious about its reach in louisiana. as a queer¬†filmmaker of color, i naturally¬†gravitate¬†towards spotlighting stories of minority groups. 
making a short film that investigated gender inequality and sexual assault in this region, and that centered on the black, female body, posed a number of challenges. historically, film has revealed a white-centered perspective even while depicting the black body. i employed impressionistic principles to reflect the full interior life of the all-black cast and to implode tropes of black communities in the rural south.

of equal importance was representing franklin, louisiana with sublime images of black life; to reclaim its sweeping landscapes as a home of black america; to paint the deep south with light, shadow and darkness as a place for black celebration and struggle. --andre rangiah, director

text:
good night sis, 
let‚Äôs talk! 
when i created this platform i didn‚Äôt realize how hard it would be for me to come up with topics. 
the truth is, although i am open to helping you heal i am still healing myself. 
and as you follow me you will see my flaws and inconsistencies show. 
that‚Äôs the thing about healing, 
it‚Äôs no perfect picture. 
like at all. 
i want to be lead by spirit when i come to you with messages. if there is nothing i receive, there is nothing i can say. 
and a lot of times... i‚Äôm working on me. 
that‚Äôs what this year is about for me. 
but let‚Äôs go deeper.
.
.
.
push through 
my push through game is not always strong. 
a lot of times a battling with myself
trying to find a balance that i have never even seen or experienced growing up 
i battle between who i am, who i was, and who i want to be. 
i‚Äôm also battling with allowing all of the best parts of me become one. 
this is my testimony. 
the ugly truths that i face everyday 
the ability and inability to pick myself up when i fall. 
because, as a healer you have to have the magic to do so. 
although i am loved and appreciated. 
i can not be all of me, without loving.. all. of. me.
you get what i‚Äôm saying, sis? 
can you relate? 
let me know. let‚Äôs talk. 
your sistar, 
deyelahdea

text:
i didn't ever think about what it meant to be a woman when i was growing up. how my reality was shaped differently than that of my friends who were boys.  not until the past year or two and the #metoo movement did i really sit uncomfortably in it, and reflect on how this shaped who i trust, how we raise our little humans, and how i feel so unprepared for these conversations.

i don't want to have to teach my girls how to hold their car keys in the "stabbing position", how to avoid being cornered in a grocery store dairy freezer by their boss, how to decide how much sexual harassment is "too much" to put up with in a job, how to balance needing a paycheque vs. wanting to feel safe.

right now they still feel so little, so vulnerable.  am i having the right conversations with them? using the right language? being inclusive and diverse in what we talk about, what we experience?  how do i both empower them and nourish their little hearts to also be open, inclusive, and loving?  how do i navigate their big feelings they have in dealing with peers and school so that they come out the other side of childhood with a strong, confident sense of self, one that isn't shaped by fear?

truly open here to book recommendations, especially ones i can read with them at bedtime.

#honestmotherhood #motherhoodunplugged #ig_motherhood #thepursuitofjoyproject #motherhood #parentingtheshitouttalife #squamishmom #raisingdaughters #momlife #candidchildhood #motherhoodthroughinstagram #parenting #littleandbrave #mother #letthembelittle #comox #comoxvalley #courtenay #courtenaybc #weareyqq #yqqcreatives #yyj #yqq #calledtobecreative #design #squamishcreatives #squamishbc #squamish #featherlitedesigns

text_retweet:
new french talk by alliance francais kl.

#repost @alliancefrancaisekl
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
this month we will have the pleasure of hosting a discussion on the issue of women's rights between rozana isa, executive director of sister in islam forum, and anne-c√©cile mailfert, founder of the french foundation "fondation des femmes". this french talk will be moderated by kartini ariffin, former host of 3r (respek, relaks, respon) who has spearheaded numerous digital media projects in the area of young women empowerment.
the speakers, both experienced activists, will share their experiences in advocating women's rights in malaysia and france and reflect on the way ahead for us: what methods can be used most effectively to advocate women's rights today? in the light of the recent #metoo movement and its ripples worldwide, to what extent are women's rights to be understood universally or adapted to specific cultural contexts? how much progress still needs to be done to ensure equal rights between men and women ?

rsvp at www.alliancefrancaise.org.my

organised by
embassy of france in malaysia
alliance fran√ßaise de kuala lumpur ------------------------------------------------------- what is french talks?

welcoming french and malaysian experts, it aims at creating a space of dialogue, and a bridge between the two countries and their cultures. this is particularly timely in this new malaysia where people are willing to express their views

text:
how #metoo is changing culture, politics, and journalism: a conversation with kuow‚Äôs sydney brownstone
#
when: tuesday, february 26, 2019 - 6:00 pm @ 6:00 pm ‚Äì 9:00 pm2019-02-26t18:00:00-08:002019-02-26t21:00:00-08:00where: campion ballroom, seattle universitywhat role does empathy play in journalism? why do sexual assault accusers go to journalists instead of the police? why does the #metoo movement keep showing us photographs of sad ladies looking out of windows?join award-winning journalist sydney brownstone for a look behind the curtain of some of her most complex and impactful reporting on rape and sexual assault. sydney will open this event with an in-depth examination of how she reports stories involving trauma. her presentation will include tips for interviewing accusers and the accused, fact checking strategies, insights about self-care for journalists and others close to trauma survivors, analysis of ‚Äúsad lady‚Äù portraits and other clich√©s in trauma reporting, and more. after her presentation, sydney will be joined in-conversation by seattle university professor sonora jha, and then the floor open for audience q&a.doors: 6 p.m.resource fair: 6-7 p.m.program: 7-8:30 p.m.resource fair continues: 8:30-9 p.m.about the speakerssydney brownstone has been called the ‚Äútrauma whisperer‚Äù for her empathy as a journalist working with survivors. she is currently the online editor at kuow.¬† sydney is an award-winning journalist who came to kuow from reporting‚Ä¶

why the need for a workplace detox?
toxic behaviour is bad for business. it‚Äôs the bottom line that feels it the greatest. heightened levels of workplace stress and anxiety results in reduced productivity, increased absenteeism and decreased profitability.
organisations where toxic behaviour is allowed to thrive will also experience low levels of employee loyalty and high levels of employee turnover. the concern here is not just the mounting recruitment costs and damage to growth in consistently taking on and training new employees; rather, it is the reputational damage to the business. perhaps you‚Äôve already received poor reviews on glass door from colleagues who have left with a negative impression of the organisation ‚Äì an impression that they‚Äôre happy (or even eager) to share online and with friends, family, potential and current customers, competitors, stakeholders and the press.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
what did i love about doing artsy shoots for my upcoming book. ?  i get to scream and scream. 1 hour of screaming forcing myself to remember and to let go. leaving my mind with nothing but silence when i'm out of breath (and left with a slight headache üòÇ). i used to be afraid of my emotions. i am not anymore. i√¶but sometimes i need to remind myself that they are there for a reason. to rinse and cleanse. to guide me in my path through life. telling me if i've stepped a bit to far left or like with these shoots. to scream my past goodbye, leaving room for new and beautiful memories. don't fear pain. listen. it's here to tell you somerhing. you just need to find a way to channel it. be it in sports, writing, entrepreneuring. embrace it and build something  beautiful. @svenssonsunniva wrote today that our body is our temple. that stuck with me. it is! worship your body. you're beautiful, don't ever forget that ‚ù§Ô∏è üì∏@jimhansenfoto .
.
.

text:
this week our sisters at @nowhitesaviors shared the stories of survivors affected by sexual violence at a safe house and rehabilitation centre called bery‚Äôs place in uganda. when we say #shematters, explain the importance of the #metoo movement, and the need to stand in unity with survivors we are not only referring to white survivors - or those from privileged backgrounds. the she matters community exists for survivors of all ethnic, religious, and socioeconomic backgrounds. 
___
we stand with the survivors who were sexually abused at the hands of a white man (and medical professional) who was advertising his desire to protect women who had survived abuse. the horrific acts which occurred at bery‚Äôs place shine a light on the white saviour complex and the belief that white men and women are somehow qualified to run programs with no experience or background checks. bery never should have been permitted to work alongside these young women. 
the government should have been monitoring bery‚Äôs place operations and inquiring why a 60+ year old man would be interested in running a safe home for young women who had survived sexual violence. 
what were his motives? 
who was supervising this home to ensure the young women, already vulnerable, were being protected? today we pledge #kalangalatoo, we stand with these incredibly courageous survivors and we demand they see justice for the crimes committed by bery glaser. 
we believe survivors. 
you are not alone. 
we‚Äôre stronger together ‚úäüèæ

this is a defining moment in hollywood for the post #metoo movement. 
this is it. this is the beginning. 
get ready. and get on board.

text_retweet:
‚Äúmy mother frequently commented to me about how unusually empathetic i could be. i always sensed she was puzzled by this part of me. not judging, but also not relating to my vulnerability for others whom i sensed to be in need or distress.  as a child, i did not realize that everyone was not wired that way.  my ability to sense heightened tensions and to ask about them caused much trouble.  asking someone what is wrong when the only measures of strength and perfection are in ‚Äîno display of difficult or non-positive feelings, was unwelcome‚Äîresented.  i was the feeler.  i felt it all. and i dared to speak of it. i have cautioned my boys that the quickest way to agitate their father, my sister, or anyone in their ‚Äúfamilies‚Äù is to ask ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs wrong? are you ok?‚Äù those ironically and consistently turned out to be fight starters, followed by confusing and painful distance and silence.  those inquiries are treated as trouble making.‚Äù

text:
girls are not toys launches as a workshop series on international women‚Äôs day 2019.
üôå
girls are not toys is a localised street art exhibition celebrating the lives of women and girls in urban and regional communities.
ü§ü
awareness raising, the project advocates the safety and wellbeing of women and girls, whilst educating about the underlying social conditions that contribute to the different types of gender violence that can be experienced over a lifetime, in our communities.
üß®
the artworks are made through a participatory workshop process, and are an opportunity for women and girls to come together to share ideas, educate others and contribute to the rising lived experience and #metoo movement.
ü•ä
girls are not toys presents fresh ideas on victim stereotyping, challenging ideas of passivity often seen in violence against women campaigns. the project exhibits images of strong, feisty women and girls in public spaces and places to flip the narrative.

more info: www.girlsarenottoys.org üì∏ tammy brennan // ashley albury with workshop participant.

text:
"a woman was raped in the centre of my town and now we are told: ‚Äúwe should have a buddy system‚Äù ‚Äúwe should carry mace‚Äù ‚Äúwe shouldn‚Äôt walk alone at night‚Äù ‚Äúwe should take uber next time‚Äù ‚Äúwe should dress differently‚Äù 
i have had it with these comments i am seeing on #socialmedia. this is my town as much as anyone. i will be able to walk four blocks to a bar without even considering myself in danger. it is not only about finding and punishing this one guy; it is about changing the global #culture to not include a vagina as a commodity. i am not giving into fear. i have gone so far as to suggest vigilantism because i want to strike fear into men as the penal system clearly does not seem a very strong deterrent. the crass messages from strangers and ‚Äòfriends‚Äô alike, the comments at parties and bars and businesses, the lurker eyeballs at the dmv. these are the challenges that women deal with every single day. it‚Äôs ridiculous, repulsive and quite frankly, blatantly random. 
just two wednesdays ago at my favourite local club, two different men touched me at separate times and places. and i am so pathetically well-trained, i have a snarky face and a wisecrack and went on my way. i didn‚Äôt want to cause a stir at my favourite bar on a popular night, especially since it was not my regular crowd of familiars. we are programmed by the #patriarchy and our dear mothers and aunts and grandmothers to curtsy out and suck it up. 
now that i am not in a marriage and travel my little route on this earth solo more often, i am experiencing a boldness that either i had mistaken for flirtation when i was younger (attention) or has actually gotten somehow subversively worse in this time of political correctness. much like racism, pushed underground as shameful, it may bubble up and bite harder. 
i simply wish that the obvious truth of shiva & shakti could be acknowledged and then embodied. it is so obvious...yin yang. we are all way beyond this level of engagement. rape and dick pics? really? sisters we must speak up at every cost on every occasion. i am not anti-man...anyone can tell you that. but i am anti neanderthal. that age has gone!"
#metoo #metoomovement #feminism

.

however, she persevered and proved this characterization wrong. she went on to host and produce her own talk show, the oprah winfrey show, and become the chairman and ceo of harpo, inc. she later launched a magazine, o, and tv network, own.
.
.
today, oprah splits time as a philanthropist, 60 minutes contributor, actor (with a leading role in the upcoming film a wrinkle in time) and brand ambassador for weight watchers -- she owns a 10 percent stake in the weight loss company.
.
.
her net worth as of feb. 15, 2018, is $2.8 billion, according to forbes, making her the richest black american.
.
.
‚Äúwhen you undervalue what you do, the world will undervalue who you are.‚Äù
.
‚Äúdoing the best at this moment puts you in the best place for the next moment‚Äù
.

.
‚Äúturn your wounds into wisdom.‚Äù .

text:
today we get to hear from myriam poizat about how socialists in ireland built a movement to legalize abortion! scaife hall 125 (cmu, 4805 frew st), 7pm. there will be childcare - please message us for details!

as we face continued attacks by the far right trump administration, we have much to learn from these major victories for the rights of working women and non-binary people. importantly, we must organize and link our struggles in solidarity to demand and win reforms, while also aiming to dispense with a capitalist system at the root of our inequality and abuse. we demand control over our bodies, our livelihoods, our workplaces, and our society. we work in political solidarity with the socialist party ireland to achieve this, and fight for such a socialist world. (picture by @bostonsocialistalternative)

text:
each of these women you can see in the picture carry a story not everybody has the strength to listen to. 
after covering on foot 10,000 kilometers, spread over 24 states in 200 districts of india, this entourage of over five thousand rape survivors concluded the garima yatra/dignity march today (22nd feb, 2019). sharing their stories of assault along the way, they raised their voices loud enough to reach every nook and corner. amongst them were women who were raped in front of their children, women who were abducted, abused and left to bleed, women who were branded as witches by fellow villagers when they reported their assault, women who were beaten up by their families for getting abused, women who were left by their husbands, women who were raped because they belong to a lower caste, women who were raped because they tried to stop another women/girl child from being abused, women who now are mothers to their rapist's child, women who are now jobless, aimless and awfully hurt, men who lost their daughters and sisters to a sexual assault. 
each of these stories is worth an instagram post, worth a hashtag, worth a blog, yet each of these stories is so horrifying that you can barely have courage to listen to them. 
while urban women or women with access to social media reported their abuses with the #metoo  movement, these uneducated and underprivileged women sought to traditional means in order to be heard. while they might have concluded their journey, it is on us, the citizens to not let their voices fade away. 
this post is a simple reminder that an abuse is an abuse even if it didn't happen in front of your eyes, a survivor is a survivor even if she/he is not related to you, a person who reports her/his assault deserves to be heard and to be supported no matter whether she/he does so via a social media account or via a rural self help groups.
- 
article by @prashastishreshtha

if not, would you like to?  would you like to believe, and know, that you are seen, heard, matter? 
what would that look like for you? 
feeling more self-confident about yourself? 
to speak up and advocate for yourself either at work, home, with family, with friends, all the above? 
to learn to set limits to take care of you and no longer have work or tasks dumped on you?

to have your hard work recognized?

to decrease that negative self-talk?

to no longer be invisible?

it is possible!  it might seem out of reach or scary, but it is possible.

it is my goal to empower women to believe in themselves.  if you would like to believe in yourself more than you currently do, let‚Äôs connect!  i offer a  discovery call to discuss what it is you are looking for and would like, how we could do that working together, and answer your questions.  i look forward to speaking with you! click link in bio @denisestyer or go to ‚§µÔ∏è www.calendly.com/denisestyer.com/empower to schedule a call üíú

text: boys need to be protected as much as girls. being male does not protect them from being preyed upon. the fact that they are naturally physically stronger than their female counterparts in no way guarantees them an advantage, because most child sexual abuse begins with mental and emotional manipulation, not brute physical force. and a boy or young man is no more of an intellectual match for the sexual predator than his female counterpart. in fact, as you see in the attached article, boys are groomed using the exact same tactics used on girls. the predators look for any vulnerability that can be exploited to their advantage. be it the promise of fame; the promise of a thriving and successful athletic career, or simply to be loved in the absence of a father. and, being the victim of these predacious deviants isn't a "my son would never allow a man to do this or that to him" situation, because the manipulation that leads to the abuse occurs in such a way that the victim doesn't even see it coming until it's too late. so please, talk to your boys and warn them against the dangers of being groomed/targeted by other males for sexual abuse. reassure them that this isn't about masculinity or sexual orientation, but the sexual deviance of predators who seek out victims to satisfy their own desires. because boys need to be protected too.....#childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #church #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #socialmedia

text:
emma thompson exited the upcoming animated film luck earlier this month because production company skydance had hired john lasseter as head of animation. in a searing letter to skydance, published by the l.a. times on tuesday, thompson put the speculation to rest: "it feels very odd to me," she wrote, "that you and your company would consider hiring someone with mr. lasseter's pattern of misconduct given the present climate in which people with the kind of power that you have can reasonably be expected to step up to the plate." lasseter left pixar in 2018 after allegations of inappropriate workplace behavior. his misconduct was so entrenched at pixar that women working there reportedly developed a technique dubbed "the lasseter" to prevent him from groping their legs. lasseter ultimately admitted to inappropriate hugging and "other missteps." nevertheless, skydance hired lasseter earlier this year, with ceo david ellison assuring employees that lasseter had "learned valuable lessons" and would henceforth "comport himself in a wholly professional manner." thompson, for her part, is having none of that.

text:
we can make a difference by... is today's challenge for #feministfebruary! again, feel free to respond to my answer and/or answer it yourself in the comments üòä
.
this is such a hard question! i think a mentality change is one of the most important things to create a more gender equal world. in (most of) the west, there's economic and political equality (on paper at least) and it's things like implicit bias, intersectionality, rape culture, double standards that need to be addressed i think. awareness raising is needed, people speaking up as they did during #metoo and so on. joining a feminist group or march, speaking up when you see something wrong. and supporting each other, listen to each other and learn about your own privileges and prejudices. i hate that this is such an individual centred answer üòÖ so collective action is important too! pressure companies, institutions, governments. there's going to be a women's strike on the 8th, so i'm going to join the protest and try and make a difference. also, collectively taking individual action towards change could bring us places too
.
.
.

congratulations to regina king for her first oscar nomination and her first win!! she took home the academy award for best supporting actress for her work in barry jenkins‚Äô james baldwin adaptation ‚Äúif beale street could talk‚Äù - a love story set in harlem that follows the star-crossed romance between two african-american youths, fonny (stephan james) and tish (kiki layne). -
‚Äúthis is an urban tragedy,‚Äù king said of the film, ‚Äúbut tragedy is something that‚Äôs experienced no matter what sex you are, no matter what race you are‚Ä¶ this film is so needed right now. we‚Äôre different in a lot of ways. absolutely, our cultures are very different, but to the core we‚Äôre really a lot alike.‚Äù
-
she added that the #metoo movement has created ‚Äúopportunities for women to find their voice,‚Äù and not just when it comes to the kinds of physical violation discussed in the film. ‚Äúeven beyond being violated sexually,‚Äù she said, ‚Äúbeing marginalized, being violated when you have put in the work to be at the table, and being denied a seat at the table‚Äîthis movement has allowed us and inspired us to say, ‚Äòno, i deserve to have a seat at the table.‚Äô‚Äù

today only see soraya chemaly of @ragebecomesher speak at explore more summit. details below.
.
"women's pleasure is not just ignored, but denied and punished." soraya
.
study after study after study (rinse, repeat) shows the ways women and girls' pain is ignored, minimized, doubted, and questioned by doctors and medical professionals. study after study after study shows the ways babies who are thought to be girls are denied anger by adults and babies who are thought to be boys have anger validated and named by adults. study after study after study talks about the orgasm gap and how women in heterosexual relationships are experiencing the most pain during sex and the least pleasure.
.
pleasure equals access to power. why? because to feel pleasure, to know pleasure is your birthright, is to have agency over your body and to get to decide what happens with your body. this is deeply threatening to the status quo especially if you are a trans woman, a black or indigenous woman, a disabled or a poor woman, or a femme.
.

text:
i got my tattoo to mark how strong i've been, and to remind myself that i'm a survivor.

i chose a lotus flower as it only grows in muddy/dirty water yet it still opens up into the most beautiful, pure flower. it's opening petals represent the expansion of the soul‚ù§Ô∏è
it is also recognised as symbolising detachment as water droplets easily slide off the petals. i see this as me detaching myself from the me that was a victim. i no longer hold that stance -
i am a survivor. 
i chose the teal colour for sexual assault awareness.

text:
in the beginning, healing was about fixing myself. i thought something was wrong with me, i was a problem that needed to be solved. then, healing became about finding myself. i thought i was lost and needed to be found. then, healing became about freeing myself. i thought if i could let go of the consequences of abuse, then i would feel better. now, healing is about loving myself unconditionally: i am not a problem, i am not lost, and i am not bound to abuse. i am on a very intentional healing journey to recover myself and my life from the consequences of incest and illness. my models of love were vicious and violent, so it has taken me over a decade to learn that unconditional love is the ability to just hold space for myself, allow myself to feel, and reframe any negative thoughts into positive and powerful ones. i am watching as love transforms me and reorients my life in the direction of truth, wholeness, and happiness. how is love transforming you? how is it reforming your life?
.
.
.
#love #healing #recovery #peace #metoo #trauma #hope #believe #selfcare

text:
i was just fired - or, my contract was not prolonged - by an international corporation. why? officially, because my performance and social skills were shit. strangely, the previous wasn't viewed as negatively before a certain incident and i had been given time to work on that - my performance has irrefutably improved, and yet, the time i was given, was scrapped. the latter, my social skills, were a non-issue.

until i blurted out that their pet high performer, a recurring face on their social media profiles, had been sexually harassing me ever since i was hired. others can confirm her inappropriate, hypersexual behaviour and another woman can confirm this bitch targets helpless, meek newbies. 
my supervisor was shocked. by my calling sexual harassment by its name, not by the act, mind you. he informed me that i made him sad and hurt her feelings. hr issued a warning against her, but she got all the pity and all the support from people. and me? when i yelled at our operations manager that his employee has been sexually victimizing me for months, he said, i quote, "i don't care about that!" he and my sv then proceeded to gaslight me and saying i always blamed everyone else... no. they know me to be very self critical. i do fucking blame all of them for being poor now because i complained about a fucking pervert!

the company parades around concepts like "psychological safety", "no retaliation policy", "non-violent communication" and "flat hierarchy". and then, they let me go and kept the groper.

once i get my last salary, i will reveal the corporation, the company i was in, and the names of the perverted animal, my sv and the operations manager.

#metoo #sexualassault #workplace #workplacebullying #workplacewellness #customprinting #sexualharassment #abuseofpower #rapeculture #survivors #sexism #everydaysexism #nosexism #endsexism #sexismintheworkplace

text: #metoo the day i lost my virginity a stranger careened by in his truck and shouted ‚Äúfaggots!‚Äù i don‚Äôt recall his face or tone of voice. what i remember is the roar of his engine and the deadening silence that sat with us, still and heavy as a tombstone. that cold night we spent together i felt you inside of me; i felt my youth fade away. the day i attended my first gay pride parade a stranger whispered ‚Äúfaggot.‚Äù i remember as he pinned me to the bed how relieving the silken sheets felt against my skin. how momentarily still they were compared to the man on top of me. for some time our movements seemed almost synchronous. me writhing below telling him to stop. his weightiness pressing me down as he went in and out, in and out. when i finally escaped from beneath him he told me to shut up. i was astounded. i felt shattered when i stood outside on his driveway, admiring his palatial estate. i wanted him to feel shattered too. that‚Äôs why i stole a crystalline drinking glass as i left and hurled it at his driveway. i watched as it split into a thousand pieces. the tiny shards refracting the glow of the lamplight on that cool summer night. the tiny shards silently refracting my pain within. it was almost a eureka moment. i realized then that i needed to beware. that boys will be boys. i believe it to be true because it is what i have lived to be true. of course i have been raped. i‚Äôm surprised that anyone would find it surprising. a world in which men exist will forever be a world in which terrible things exists. i am so grateful that people bravely share their stories of tragedy and pain. it is education. it is how the world will improve. i also firmly believe that there will never be a void of harmful people. so when you are 21 and a stranger at least a decade older than you tempts you away from your friends, tempts you with cocaine and sex, you say must say no. when you roam the midnight streets alone and drunken, terrible events may materialize in an instant. this world is very beautiful and very dangerous; there are forever dangerous people amongst us. be brave. be pragmatic. be magnanimous. share your story. love, kevin

i felt my youth fade away. the day i attended my first gay pride parade a stranger whispered ‚Äúfaggot.‚Äù i remember as he pinned me to the bed how relieving the silken sheets felt against my skin. how momentarily still they were compared to the man on top of me. for some time our movements seemed almost synchronous. me writhing below telling him to stop. his weightiness pressing me down as he went in and out, in and out. when i finally escaped from beneath him he told me to shut up. i was astounded. i felt shattered when i stood outside on his driveway, admiring his palatial estate. i wanted him to feel shattered too. that‚Äôs why i stole a crystalline drinking glass as i left and hurled it at his driveway. i watched as it split into a thousand pieces. the tiny shards refracting the glow of the lamplight on that cool summer night. the tiny shards silently refracting my pain within. it was almost a eureka moment. i realized then that i needed to beware. that boys will be boys. i believe it to be true because it is what i have lived to be true. of course i have been raped. i‚Äôm surprised that anyone would find it surprising. a world in which men exist will forever be a world in which terrible things exists. i am so grateful that people bravely share their stories of tragedy and pain. it is education. it is how the world will improve. i also firmly believe that there will never be a void of harmful people. so when you are 21 and a stranger at least a decade older than you tempts you away from your friends, tempts you with cocaine and sex, you say must say no. when you roam the midnight streets alone and drunken, terrible events may materialize in an instant. this world is very beautiful and very dangerous; there are forever dangerous people amongst us. be brave. be pragmatic. be magimous. share your story. love, kevin

of his power, force the feeling 
of dependence?

does the whoosh of grass get louder,

on his inner house:

.
.
.

text:
at the age of three
a life was ruined
in a very short span of time

in three minutes
a life was ruined
in the hands
of a perverted father

the child grew to hate him
to hate with a burning passion
to hate him with every inch
of their tiny, feminine body

the child grew up in a better home
they moved away from the evil
of the father who ruined their life
(dm me if you want to know the whole story)

text:
i find the language surrounding masculinity often gets misunderstood.

traditional masculinity emphasises traits like physical strength, emotional stoicism, projected self-sufficiency, and heterosexual dominance over women, wealth, professional success, power, risk taking, invulnerability, virility, control, dominance, excessive competitiveness and a rejection of femininity.

so when we hear people talking about traditional or toxic masculinity, this üëÜüèªis what they are talking about.

it is not an attack on traditional values.

it is not saying all masculinity is toxic.

now go spread this lesson far and wide because when people understand this distinction, we can start talking about how we can all be better human beings and make this world kinder. üåç

‚Å£‚†Ä

‚Å£‚†Ä
have you ever thought about trying meditation?‚Å£‚†Ä

meet our wcw obiageli ohiakim @oby_o üòÅ

she is a lawyer, currently working as an in-house counsel at a quasi-government agency in abuja, nigeria. she is also the founder of projectbaby nigeria and a blogger at www.playsuitsandlawsuits.com¬†(a parenting/lifestyle blog). she shared below üëáüëásome insightful tips on child development. have a great read.
@oby_o ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ 
dear mom of boys,

just a friendly reminder that now is the time to raise kind men.üôèüèæ i am asking you to please talk to your sons about women‚Äôs rights, about kindness, about boundaries and limits, teach them to not put up with disrespectful ‚Äújokes‚Äù about women. .
.
i just heard my 4 year old call his nanny ‚Äúfat‚Äù and even though it may have seemed innocent, it was an opportunity to speak up as a mother, as a woman and as an employer. teach your boys that it isn‚Äôt their place to comment on a woman‚Äôs body. because of you, they will grow up to take notice of a woman‚Äôs smart brain, witty humor or kind heart.üíï
.
.
keep holding your boys responsible for their actions and the outcomes. keep teaching them to keep their hands to themselves. to not resort to violence, to use their words. boys will not be boys! boys will be kind! üôåüèæ
.
.
i am asking you to start this now - when they are still little boys; before they get a chance to get their answers online, or from the wrong people. 
let‚Äôs raise a generation of men who will read about the #metoo movement in the history books and shake their heads in disbelief.

text:
we‚Äôre celebrating some more wonderful women on our campus in the lead up to international womxn‚Äôs day next week! prof. rebecca major (her/she) is a phd candidate in indigenous public policy at the johnson shoyama graduate school of public policy at the university of saskatchewan. her dissertation investigates indigenous policy change in the context of land claims and identity rights. she is currently faculty in the department of political science at the university of windsor. prof. major started at the university of windsor july 2018. 
outside of academia, prof. major has worked in several capacities in m√©tis administration. she has previously been elected as area representative, western region 2a, m√©tis nation-saskatchewan; manager of intergovernmental affairs; and a policy advisor in both environment and intergovernmental affairs for the m√©tis nation-saskatchewan.  she states she became involved politically because she felt it was her responsibility as an educated person to contribute back to her community. 
her areas of interest include canadian indigenous public policy; indigenous governance, national and international; policy of identity and membership; indigenous land and governance claims; policy learning; and the united nations declaration on the rights of indigenous peoples. ‚Äúinternational women‚Äôs day is significant to me because i think it‚Äôs important to honour women and the rights our forebearers fought for. we are still dealing with violence, mysogenistic language and treatement, so this assists in providing an opportunity to discuss the continuing issues for women. with the #metoo movement we are opening conversations that need to take place, and for me, it is imperative we eliminate the marginalization of people in canada, and that includes women, indigenous peoples, and other minorities.‚Äù -prof. rebecca major
name: Womxn's Centre

it‚Äôs whatawomanwednesday: and we can‚Äôt help wanting to celebrate teacher melissa berton, and the students of the oakwood school in l.a. for their short documentary win for period. end of sentence! she told thr that, ‚Äúthe project was born because her students in l.a. and people in india wanted to make a "human rights difference.‚Äù she told abc7 that, ‚Äúoriginally, the short documentary was a marketing tool for their bigger vision‚Äîa nonprofit they created called the pad project,‚Äù whose ‚Äúmission was to get a machine that creates biodegradable pads to a rural village in india,‚Äù after they learned that ‚Äúthe taboos around menstruation in india and the lack of hygienic sanitary products leads to almost a third of indian girls missing school during their periods.‚Äù she explained that, ‚Äúthe students were in charge of fundraising, creating the nonprofit and bringing the documentary to life.‚Äù and that, ‚Äúseven executive producers on the project are either in college or in grad school and several associate producers are still in high school.‚Äù congrats on succeeding with the mission to make a difference on a human‚Äîand woman‚Äôs rights issue. üí™

text:
in an effort to remain transparent, let me clear a few things up (üé§is this thing on?).
.
i‚Äôm not here to build a following based on a perfectly curated feed or playing it safe by staying in one lane.
.
i do the lifestyle stuff because i enjoy it, plain and simple. i like sharing what i love in case others might find out they love it too. i like encouraging, empowering, laughing with, and lifting up other women and parents.
.
but i also stand for things so important to me that silence is not an option. i will fight for injustice. i will stand with survivors; of #metoo and #churchtoo - i will preach when there‚Äôs a need to preach and shut up & listen to women and poc.
.
as a feminist, i do not hate men. i‚Äôm married to an extraordinary man. a man who sees me as his equal partner in all things.
.
normally these topics are banished to my twitter account, sometimes never to be known by my instagram followers. but it‚Äôs all me, i‚Äôm not living two separate lives.
.
i am a mom.
i am a wife.
i am an author.
i love makeup and fashion and glitter.
i love theological debates and learning from the mistakes the church has made.
i am painfully aware of my white privilege and solemnly swear to listen & learn, and not expect poc to do that emotional work for me.
i am an ally, now and always, and i grieve with all those who‚Äôs church kicked them out and slammed the door in their face yesterday (quite literally).
.
if you don‚Äôt stand for something, you stand for nothing. complacency is the death of empathy, the beginning of the end of human decency.
.
if i continued to fill my feed with nothing but fluff to build my business, without revealing my truest self to you in an effort to keep followers; i‚Äôd be a fraud.
.
so here i am, in all my complicated glory. an ally walking through the wilderness of deconstruction. love me, hate me, follow, unfollow. come for the witty banter, stay for the hard things.‚úåüèºüåàüíõ.
.
.
.
.

throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign‚Äôs use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there ‚Äúcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating‚Äù. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday‚Äôs hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
this is a photo of me taken last march. i was in los angeles. it was just days after the oscars. it was international women‚Äôs day. it was the wake of #metoo.

i had just finished a women‚Äôs program for a group of hollywood producers, screen writers and guild advocate groups committed to filming more stories and casting more actors that feature women, diversity and equality. 
it was cool - but let me be real honest - i am way way more passionate about hearing and sharing the stories of women here in our community, than the ones under the bright lights of hollywood. 
i‚Äôd rather gather us up with mud on my boots, or barefoot in stretchy pants and a sweater, than in heels and spanx. 
i‚Äôd rather hug and share our real stories of hard, sad, love, balance, sisterhood and strength, than listen or read stories of those i will never know.

i believe that there is a quiet and beautiful revolution happening amongst us - here - not in films and places afar. 
and i believe if we allow ourselves to pause, listen, connect and explore - we will see it with fresh eyes and feel it with a full heart.

it‚Äôs why i stepped away from corporate with a dream of building a community and programming through the lens of wellness and nurturing self care through community, connection, creativity, mindfulness and movement. 
it‚Äôs why, one year later, i couldn‚Äôt be more excited and hopeful in extending an invitation to an international women‚Äôs day event taking place - here - not in hollywood. 
i would love if you would join me‚Ä¶us‚Ä¶here‚Ä¶now! will you be a part of this?  visit the links in my profile to sign-up to be a part of this! 
p.s. i know there are zillion reasons why you think you can‚Äôt or shouldn‚Äôt‚Ä¶work, kids, appointments, etc‚Ä¶ but listen ladies, it‚Äôs international women‚Äôs day!  book a sitter, take a personal day, reschedule an appointment‚Ä¶let us celebrate you...because, my dear one, you are amazing!
.

text_retweet:
reposted from @cleezereport -  last year bette midler renewed allegation geraldo rivera groped her... actor posts video of 1991 interview in which she describes alleged assault, saying tv host and producer pushed drugs ‚Äòunder my nose‚Äô

bette midler renewed an allegation of 1970s sexual misconduct against geraldo rivera on thursday, a day after rivera called the news business ‚Äúflirty‚Äù amid matt lauer‚Äôs dismissal by nbc.

in the tweet posted by the actor-singer and confirmed by her publicist, she included a video from the 1991 interview with barbara walters in which midler made the allegation against rivera. ‚Äútomorrow is my birthday. i feel like this video was a gift from the universe to me. geraldo may have apologized for his tweets supporting matt lauer, but he has yet to apologize for this,‚Äù midler posted, adding the harassment-solidarity hashtag ‚Äú#metoo‚Äù. a representative for rivera did not immediately respond to a request for comment. fox news channel, which currently employs rivera but did not in the 70s, did not immediately comment on midler‚Äôs post.

in the clip, midler hesitates in recounting what she alleges happened with rivera during his visit to interview her in the early 70s, saying it will get her in trouble. ‚Äúget in a little trouble,‚Äù walters encourages her.

after rivera and a producer left their tv crew in another room, they ‚Äúpushed me into my bathroom. they broke two poppers and pushed them under my nose and proceeded to grope me,‚Äù she said. ‚Äúpoppers‚Äù is slang for the alkyl nitrites class of drugs. ‚Äúi did not offer myself up on the altar of geraldo rivera,‚Äù said midler, calling his behavior ‚Äúunseemly‚Äù. after midler tells walters that she had no way of knowing ‚Äúthese things are going to come back to haunt you‚Äù, walters suggests they discuss other subjects.

walters opened up the topic by asking about midler‚Äôs reaction to rivera‚Äôs 1991 autobiography exposing myself, including what walters called his account of a ‚Äútorrid sexual affair‚Äù with midler, whom he labeled ‚Äúinsatiable‚Äù. midler smiles, saying she was glad the book ran counter to her image at the time of the interview as that of a ‚Äúsomewhat strait-laced‚Äù older lady.

when skydance announced that they were hiring john lasseter ‚Äî who has multiple allegations of inappropriate behavior in the workplace ‚Äî as head of skydance animation, many members of the company and the industry-at-large were shocked by this news.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

washington examiner
